<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1261,1430]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
This species, originally described from Southern Brazil, was not examined in this work. It is one of four 
<taxonomicName box="[151,300,1297,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,300,1297,1322]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Holopothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with the body mostly brown but having few abdominal segments pale, with only the pelta and abdominal segment II being yellow in 
<taxonomicName box="[582,718,1333,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balteatus">
<emphasis box="[582,718,1333,1358]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H. balteatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The key in 
<bibRefCitation box="[859,1147,1333,1358]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" refId="ref59437" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The thrips of Central and South America: an introduction (Insecta: Thysanoptera). Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article">Mound &amp; Marullo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
differentiates this species from 
<taxonomicName box="[212,313,1370,1393]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis box="[212,313,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">H. pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the size of postocellar setae and metanotal reticulation, and this step has been repeated in the key presented here.
</paragraph>
